Looking at positive affect and life expectancy for six countries; Canada, Peru, UK, Uganda, India and New Zealand

data<- filter(df, country== "Canada" | country== "Peru"| country== "United Kingdom"| country== "Uganda"| country== "India"| country== "New Zealand")
view(data)

Static plot

my_plot1 <- data %>%
  group_by(year)%>%
  ggplot(aes(x=`Positive affect`, y=`Healthy life expectancy at birth`, colour = country))+
  geom_point(size=2)

my_plot1

Animated plot

my_plot2 <- data %>%
  group_by(year)%>%
  ggplot(aes(x=`Positive affect`, y=`Healthy life expectancy at birth`, colour = country))+
  geom_point(size=2)+
  labs(x = "Positive Affect", title = "Health Life Expectancy at Birth") +
  transition_time(year)+
  shadow_mark(past = T, future=F, alpha=0.3)


animate(my_plot2)

Then add the year as a subtitle.

my_plot3 <- data %>%
  group_by(year)%>%
  ggplot(aes(x=`Positive affect`, y=`Healthy life expectancy at birth`, colour = country))+
  geom_point(size=2)+
  labs(x = "Positive Affect", y = "Health Life Expectancy at Birth", title = "Positive Affect and Life Expectancy by Year by Country",
       subtitle = "Year = {closest_state}") +
  transition_states(year)+
  shadow_mark(past = T, future=F, alpha=0.3)


animate(my_plot3)

Can see with regression line - can see Peru and Uganda are going up over time but India is staying relatively level.

my_plot4 <- data %>%
  group_by(year)%>%
  ggplot(aes(x=`Positive affect`, y=`Healthy life expectancy at birth`, colour = country))+
  geom_point(size=2)+
  geom_smooth(method="lm")
  labs(x = "Positive Affect", y = "Health Life Expectancy at Birth", title = "Positive Affect and Life Expectancy by Year by Country")

Make linear model of life expectancy predicred by positive affect.

model1<-lm(`Healthy life expectancy at birth` ~ 1, data=data)
model2<-lm(`Healthy life expectancy at birth` ~ `Positive affect` , data=data)

Compare the models

anova(model1, model2)

Try making a mixed model?

model.full <- lmer(`Healthy life expectancy at birth` ~ `Positive affect` +(1|country) +(1|year), data = data )

model.null <- lmer(`Healthy life expectancy at birth` ~ (1|country) +(1|year), data = data )

Full model does seem to be a better predictor.

anova(model.full, model.null)
